[3] Cholera, indigenous people - India (Madhya Pradesh)
Date: Sat 24 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: NewKerala.com [edited]
<http://www.newkerala.com/news.php?action=fullnews&id=25501>

At least 29 members of a rare tribe in Dhindori district in Madhya Pradesh
have died and several more have taken ill in the past few days due to
cholera. The primitive Baiga tribe has been hit hard by a number of
waterborne diseases in the recent times. The regular outbreaks of cholera,
malaria, gastroenteritis, diarrhea, and jaundice have become a great cause
of concern for the authorities.
"7 people have been suffering in the village from cholera over 15 days. The
doctors have come to the village now. But, still many people are suffering
from it," said Karmu Baiga, a tribal [representative?]. However,
authorities say the medical team has been working 24 hours in the district
to keep the situation under control.
Dr. B.N. Sharma said the deaths have been caused due to the consumption of
contaminated water and the general eating habits of the tribe. "The deaths
are mainly due to cholera because of contaminated water and food. They live
in very unhygienic conditions. The lifestyle of this tribe is such that
they eat stale food and drink water from anywhere," he said.
The Baiga tribe of Madhya Pradesh are the indigenous people who have lived
in the forested areas of districts Mandla Balaghat Bilaspur and Rajnandgaon
since time immemorial.
[Byline: Ravindra Dubey]
