[6] Cholera - Guinea-Bissau
Date: Fri, 30 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: UNICEF [edited]
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/HMYT-6GQM85?OpenDocument>

Guinea-Bissau continues its emergency activities in the ongoing fight
against a deadly cholera outbreak, in collaboration with the Ministry of
Health and other partners. UNICEF has rushed essential supplies to affected
populations, including the provision of oral re-hydration salt packets,
disinfectants and logistic support, along with essential drugs and medical
supplies (e.g. sodium lactate solution and glucose injections). These
medicines and supplies are critical as an immediate response to prevent
dehydration and death.
As of 28 Sep 2005, 16 678 cases and 284 deaths have been reported in
Guinea-Bissau since the beginning of the cholera outbreak in Jun 2005. As a
result of concerted efforts by the government and national and
international partners, a reduction in the cases and deaths has been noted
over the past 4 weeks. From a peak of 2088 cases and 53 deaths during the
week of 22-28 Aug 2005, there has been a continuous decline in cases,
although the situation is still critical: during the week of 19-25 Sep
2005, 903 cases and 7 deaths were reported.
"We are working to ensure that no more unnecessary deaths due to cholera,
especially among children, occur," said Dr. Nilda Lambo, UNICEF
Guinea-Bissau's Health Officer. "Beyond the immediate response to the
current epidemic, we continue to work closely with the Government and
partners for the promotion of sanitary and hygienic practices."
--
