[8] Cholera - The Gambia
Date: Wed, 28 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Daily Observer [edited]
<http://www.observer.gm/enews/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2032&Itemid=33>

The department of state for Health (DoSH) has alerted the general public to
the outbreak of cholera in the country.
According to a press release issued by DoSH yesterday, 27 Sep 2005, a small
number of people have already contracted the disease and admitted at the
Royal Victoria Teaching Hospital.
It added that the confirmed cases have a history of traveling outside The
Gambia "for one reason or another." In view of the highly contagious
nature of the disease, the release stated, the Department of State for
Health has called on the general public, especially those planning to
travel outside The Gambia, to be "very vigilant."
"Reliable sources indicate that the West African bloc is the most affected
region in the cholera outbreak. It's hereby recommended that those who plan
traveling to the sub-region should consider the inherent risk involved. If
for any reason that individuals must travel, the following preventive
measures are to be observed strictly: To prepare and pre-pack their own
drinking water and foodstuff to be used during the course of their stay; to
exercise maximum personal hygiene at all times; to properly wash fresh
foods and fruits before consumption; to wash hands properly after using
toilet facilities before handling food and water; to thoroughly cook
foodstuff well before consumption," the release stated.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This report suggests that all the cases diagnosed are imported from other
countries in West Africa, but no specific information is given. Last
week's cholera update suggested local acquisition of cases. - Mod.LL]
