[9] Cholera - Uganda, Congo DR
Date: Wed, 28 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and New Vision (Kampala)


The health ministry has closed all markets along the Uganda-Congo border
after establishing that the current cholera outbreak emerged from the DR
Congo. The ministry also banned transportation of fish fastened on bonnets
[car hoods] and selling juice in water bottles, saying it was the quickest
way of spreading cholera.
Health state minister Capt. Mike Mukula said they closed the border markets
because districts near them would be easily affected as people moved in and
out of the country. He said 4 people had died out of the 74 cases reported
in the last week in the districts of Kotido, Nebbi, Arua, Kasese,
Bundibugyo, Masindi and Kampala. Mukula said they would also close Kampala
buildings, markets, butcher shops and other shops with poor hygiene, citing
butcher shops in Kalerwe and Mulago.
--
